 <exercise xml:id="laplace-direct-integral">
  <!-- <title>Computing a Laplace Transform Directly from the Definition</title> -->

  <statement workspace="1in">
    <p>
      Using only the definition,
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{f(t)\}(s) = \int_{0}^{\infty} e^{-st} f(t)\, dt,
    </me>

    <p>
      compute the Laplace transform of the function
    <m>
      f(t) = t e^{-2t}.
    </m>
    </p>


    <p>
      Do <em>not</em> use a Laplace transform table; evaluate the integral by hand.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      You should compute
    </p>

    <me>
      \int_{0}^{\infty} t e^{-st} e^{-2t}\, dt
      =
      \int_{0}^{\infty} t e^{-(s+2)t}\, dt.
    </me>

    <p>
      Recall the standard integral (integration by parts):
    </p>

    <me>
      \int_{0}^{\infty} t e^{-a t}\, dt = \frac{1}{a^{2}},
      \qquad \text{for } a &gt; 0.
    </me>

    <p>
      Here, <m>a = s+2</m>.  
      Make sure to justify why <m>s+2 &gt; 0</m> is required for convergence.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      For <m>s &gt; -2</m>,
      <me>
        \mathcal{L}\{t e^{-2t}\}(s)
        = \frac{1}{(s+2)^{2}}.
      </me>
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      By definition of the Laplace transform,
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow> \mathcal{L}\{t e^{-2t}\}(s)
      \amp =
      \int_{0}^{\infty} t e^{-st} e^{-2t}\, dt </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp =
      \int_{0}^{\infty} t e^{-(s+2)t}\, dt. </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      For the integral to converge, we require
      <m>s+2 &gt; 0</m>.
      Let <m>a = s+2</m>.  
      Then the integral becomes
    </p>

    <me>
      \int_{0}^{\infty} t e^{-a t}\, dt.
    </me>

    <p>
      Integrate by parts:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{aligned}
      \int_{0}^{\infty} t e^{-a t}\, dt
    \amp = \left[ -\frac{t}{a} e^{-a t} \right]_{0}^{\infty}
         + \frac{1}{a} \int_{0}^{\infty} e^{-a t}\, dt \\[1ex]
      \amp = 0 + \frac{1}{a} \left[ -\frac{1}{a} e^{-a t} \right]_{0}^{\infty} \\[1ex]
      \amp = \frac{1}{a^{2}}.
      \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>
      Substituting <m>a = s+2</m>, we obtain
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{t e^{-2t}\}(s)
      = \frac{1}{(s+2)^{2}}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This is valid for <m>s &gt; -2</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>

</exercise>   

<exercise xml:id="inverse-laplace-basic">
  <!-- <title>Computing an Inverse Laplace Transform</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Compute the inverse Laplace transform of
    </p>

    <me>
      F(s) = \frac{3}{s-2} \;+\; \frac{5}{s^{2}+4}.
    </me>
    
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Recall the standard Laplace transform identities.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <m>\mathcal{L}\{e^{at}\} = \dfrac{1}{s-a}</m> for <m>s &gt; a</m>.
      </li>

      <li>
        <m>\mathcal{L}\{\sin(bt)\} = \dfrac{b}{s^{2}+b^{2}}</m>.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Match each term of <m>F(s)</m> with one of these standard forms.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      <m>f(t) = \mathcal{L}^{-1}\{F(s)\}(t)
      = 3e^{2t} + \tfrac{5}{2}\sin(2t).</m>
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We compute the inverse Laplace transform term by term.
    </p>

    <p>
      First,
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{3}{s-2}
      \quad\longrightarrow\quad
      3e^{2t},
    </me>

    <p>
      since <m>\mathcal{L}\{e^{2t}\} = \dfrac{1}{s-2}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Next,
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{5}{s^{2}+4}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Note that
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{\sin(2t)\}
      = \frac{2}{s^{2}+4}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore,
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{5}{s^{2}+4}
      = \frac{5}{2} \cdot \frac{2}{s^{2}+4}
      \quad\longrightarrow\quad
      \frac{5}{2}\sin(2t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Combining both parts gives
    </p>

    <me>
      f(t) = \mathcal{L}^{-1}\{F(s)\}(t)
      = 3e^{2t} + \frac{5}{2}\sin(2t).
    </me>

  </solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-derivatives-ode">
  <!-- <title>Solving an ODE Using Laplace Transforms of Derivatives</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Use the Laplace transform to solve the initial value problem
    </p>

    <me>
      y' + 3y = e^{-2t}, \qquad y(0) = 5.
    </me>

  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Recall the Laplace transform of a first derivative:
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{y'\}(s) = sY(s) - y(0).
    </me>

    <p>
      Also use that
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{e^{-2t}\}(s) = \frac{1}{s+2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      After applying the Laplace transform, solve for <m>Y(s)</m> and 
      rewrite it in a form suitable for taking an inverse transform.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      The solution to the IVP is
    </p>

    <me>
      y(t) = 4e^{-3t} + e^{-2t}.
    </me>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Take the Laplace transform of both sides of
    </p>

    <me>
      y' + 3y = e^{-2t},
    </me>

    <p>
      using <m>y(0)=5</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      First compute <m>\mathcal{L}\{y'\}</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{y'\}(s) = sY(s) - y(0) = sY(s) - 5.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore,
    </p>

    <me>
      sY(s) - 5 + 3Y(s) = \frac{1}{s+2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Combine terms:
    </p>

    <me>
      (s + 3)Y(s) - 5 = \frac{1}{s+2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve for <m>Y(s)</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      (s+3)Y(s)
      = \frac{1}{s+2} + 5
      = \frac{1 + 5(s+2)}{s+2}
      = \frac{5s + 11}{s+2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus,
    </p>

    <me>
      Y(s)
      = \frac{5s + 11}{(s+3)(s+2)}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Perform partial fraction decomposition.  
      Write
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{5s + 11}{(s+3)(s+2)}
      = \frac{A}{s+3} + \frac{B}{s+2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Then
    </p>

    <me>
      5s + 11 = A(s+2) + B(s+3).
    </me>

    <p>
      Expand:
    </p>

    <me>
      5s + 11 = (A+B)s + (2A + 3B).
    </me>

    <p>
      Match coefficients:
    </p>

    <me>
      A + B = 5, \qquad 2A + 3B = 11.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve the system:
    </p>

    <me>
      A = 4, \qquad B = 1.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore,
    </p>

    <me>
      Y(s) = \frac{4}{s+3} + \frac{1}{s+2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Take inverse Laplace transforms term by term:
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{4}{s+3}\right\} = 4e^{-3t},
      \qquad
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s+2}\right\} = e^{-2t}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore the solution is
    </p>

    <me>
      y(t) = 4e^{-3t} + e^{-2t}.
    </me>
  </solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-convolution-easy">
  <!-- <title>Computing a Convolution via the Inverse Laplace Transform</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Using the convolution theorem, compute the inverse Laplace transform of
    </p>

    <me>
      F(s) = \frac{1}{s(s+2)}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Do <em>not</em> use partial fractions.  
      Instead, express <m>F(s)</m> as a product of simpler transforms and use
      the convolution formula.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Recall that
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{1\}(s) = \frac{1}{s},
      \qquad
      \mathcal{L}\{e^{-2t}\}(s) = \frac{1}{s+2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      The convolution theorem states:
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\{F(s)G(s)\}
      = (f * g)(t)
      = \int_{0}^{t} f(\tau)\, g(t-\tau)\, d\tau.
    </me>

    <p>
      Use <m>f(t)=1</m> and <m>g(t)=e^{-2t}</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      <m>\mathcal{L}^{-1}\!\left\{\dfrac{1}{s(s+2)}\right\}(t)
      = \frac{1 - e^{-2t}}{2}.</m>
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We begin by writing
    </p>

    <me>
      F(s) = \frac{1}{s} \cdot \frac{1}{s+2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Then
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s}\right\} = 1,
      \qquad
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s+2}\right\} = e^{-2t}.
    </me>

    <p>
      By the convolution theorem,
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\{F(s)\}(t)
      = (1 * e^{-2t})(t)
      = \int_{0}^{t} 1 \cdot e^{-2(t-\tau)}\, d\tau.
    </me>

    <p>
      Compute the integral:
    </p>

    <me>
      \int_{0}^{t} e^{-2(t-\tau)}\, d\tau
      = e^{-2t} \int_{0}^{t} e^{2\tau}\, d\tau.
    </me>

    <me>
      = e^{-2t} \left[\frac{1}{2} e^{2\tau}\right]_{0}^{t}
      = e^{-2t} \left(\frac{1}{2}e^{2t} - \frac{1}{2}\right)
      = \frac{1 - e^{-2t}}{2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore,
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\!\left\{\frac{1}{s(s+2)}\right\}(t)
      = \frac{1 - e^{-2t}}{2}.
    </me>
  </solution>

</exercise>

</page>
<page>

<exercise xml:id="dirac-delta-impulse-response">
  <!-- <title>Impulse Response with the Dirac Delta Function</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the initial value problem
    </p>

    <me>
      y'' + 4y = \delta(t - \pi), 
      \qquad 
      y(0) = 0,\;
      y'(0) = 0.
    </me>

    <p>
      Use the Laplace transform and the identity
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{\delta(t-a)\} = e^{-as},
    </me>

    <p>
      to find the solution <m>y(t)</m>.  
      Your final answer should be written using a unit step function 
      <m>u(t-\pi)</m>.
    </p>

  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Let <m>Y(s) = \mathcal{L}\{y(t)\}</m>.  
      Use the Laplace transform formulas:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><m>\mathcal{L}\{y''\} = s^{2}Y(s) - s y(0) - y'(0)</m></li>
      <li><m>\mathcal{L}\{y\} = Y(s)</m></li>
      <li><m>\mathcal{L}\{\delta(t-\pi)\} = e^{-\pi s}</m></li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      After solving for <m>Y(s)</m>, recall that
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\!\left\{\frac{1}{s^{2}+4}\right\} = \frac{1}{2}\sin(2t)
    </me>

    <p>
      and apply the time‑shift rule
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\{e^{-as}F(s)\} 
      = u(t-a)\, f(t-a).
    </me>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      The solution is
    </p>

    <me>
      y(t) = 
      \tfrac{1}{2}\, u(t-\pi)\, \sin\!\bigl(2(t-\pi)\bigr).
    </me>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Apply the Laplace transform to both sides of
    </p>

    <me>
      y'' + 4y = \delta(t-\pi),
      \qquad
      y(0)=0,\; y'(0)=0.
    </me>

    <p>
      Compute <m>\mathcal{L}\{y''\}</m> using the initial conditions:
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{y''\}
      = s^{2}Y(s) - s y(0) - y'(0)
      = s^{2}Y(s).
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus the transformed equation is
    </p>

    <me>
      s^{2}Y(s) + 4Y(s) = e^{-\pi s}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Factor out <m>Y(s)</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      (s^{2} + 4) Y(s) = e^{-\pi s}.
    </me>

    <p>
      So
    </p>

    <me>
      Y(s) = \frac{e^{-\pi s}}{s^{2} + 4}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Now apply the inverse Laplace transform.  
      We use the time‑shift rule:
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\!\left\{\frac{1}{s^{2}+4}\right\}
      = \frac{1}{2}\sin(2t),
    </me>

    <p>
      hence
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\!\left\{\frac{e^{-\pi s}}{s^{2}+4}\right\}
      = u(t-\pi)\,\frac{1}{2}\sin\!\bigl(2(t-\pi)\bigr).
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore, the solution to the IVP is
    </p>

    <me>
      y(t) 
      = 
      \tfrac{1}{2}\, u(t-\pi)\, \sin\!\bigl(2(t-\pi)\bigr).
    </me>

    <p>
    <figure xml:id="dirac-impulse-plot">
  <caption>Response to a Dirac Delta Impulse at <m>t=\pi</m>.</caption>
  <image width="75%">
                  <description>
The graph shows a function that stays at zero until time t equals pi, where a vertical dashed line marks an impulse. After that point, the graph becomes a small sine wave that rises to about one‑half, then falls to about negative one‑half, repeating in a smooth oscillation.
  </description>
    <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

  % Axis limits
  \begin{axis}[
      width=13cm,
      height=7cm,
      xmin=0, xmax=6.5,
      ymin=-0.6, ymax=0.6,
      axis lines=middle,
      xlabel={$t$},
      ylabel={$y(t)$},
      xtick={0,1.5708,3.1416,4.7124,6.2832},
      xticklabels={$0$, $\pi/2$, $\pi$, $3\pi/2$, $2\pi$},
      ytick={-0.5,0,0.5},
      grid=both,
      grid style={gray!20},
      major grid style={gray!30},
      domain=0:6.2832,
      samples=400
    ]

    % Blue response curve: y(t) = 0 for t &lt; pi, = 0.5*sin(2*(t-pi)) for t>=pi
    \addplot[blue, very thick, domain=0:3.1416] {0};
    \addplot[blue, very thick, domain=3.1416:6.2832] {0.5*sin(deg(2*(x-3.1416)))};

    % Vertical dashed red line at t = pi
    \addplot[red, dashed, very thick] coordinates {(3.1416,-0.6) (3.1416,0.6)};

    % Legend
    \addlegendentry{$y(t)=\tfrac12\sin(2(t-\pi))u(t-\pi)$}
    % \addlegendentry{Impulse at $t=\pi$}

  \end{axis}

\end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>

</figure>
</p>

  </solution>

</exercise>

</page>

<exercise xml:id="vector-geometry-one-task">
  <!-- <title>Constructing \(\vec{u} - \tfrac12\,\vec{v}\) from a Diagram</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Vectors <m>\vec{u}</m> (blue) and <m>\vec{v}</m> (red) appear in <xref ref="fig-uv-largegrid"/>. 
      Draw the vector
      <m>\vec{u} - \tfrac12\,\vec{v}</m> on the same grid. 
      
    </p>

    <p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-uv-largegrid">
      <caption>Use the grid to construct <m>\vec{u} - \tfrac12\,\vec{v}</m>.</caption>
      <image width="80%">
             <description>
        Large coordinate grid with two vectors from the origin: u in blue points up-and-right; v in red points up and slightly more steeply.
      </description>
        <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]

  % --- Large grid and axes ---
  \draw[gray!50] (-1.5,-2.5) grid (8.5,6.5);
  \draw[->] (-1.5,0) -- (8.8,0) node[right] {$x$};
  \draw[->] (0,-2.5) -- (0,6.8) node[above] {$y$};

  % --- Given vectors (diagram-only; no coordinates shown in text) ---
  % u (blue): choose a clear up-right vector
  \draw[->, very thick, blue] (0,0) -- (5,2)
    node[midway, below right] {$\vec{u}$};

  % v (red): a steeper up-left-ish than u? Keep tail at origin; up-and-left would cross origin; 
  % we instead choose up and a bit left relative to u's direction but still in first quadrant.
  \draw[->, very thick, red] (0,0) -- (2,6)
    node[midway, left] {$\vec{v}$};

  % Axis tick marks (light)
  \foreach \x in {-1,0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8}
    \draw[gray!80] (\x,0.1)--(\x,-0.1);
  \foreach \y in {-2,-1,0,1,2,3,4,5,6}
    \draw[gray!80] (0.1,\y)--(-0.1,\y);

\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      First construct <m>\tfrac12\,\vec{v}</m> (same direction as <m>\vec{v}</m> but half the length). 
      Then reverse it to obtain <m>-\tfrac12\,\vec{v}</m>.
      Place the tail of <m>-\tfrac12\,\vec{v}</m> at the tip of <m>\vec{u}</m>; 
      the vector from the origin to the new tip is <m>\vec{u} - \tfrac12\,\vec{v}</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      The requested vector is <m>\vec{w}=\vec{u} - \tfrac12\,\vec{v}</m>; 
      it can be drawn from the origin to the tip of <m>\vec{u} + \bigl(-\tfrac12\,\vec{v}\bigr)</m>, as illustrated in <xref ref="fig-uv-solution"/>.
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We sketch <m>\tfrac12\,\vec{v}</m> (half the red vector in the same direction), reverse it to get <m>-\tfrac12\,\vec{v}</m>, 
      and place its tail at the tip of <m>\vec{u}</m>.  
      The vector from the origin to that final tip is <m>\vec{w}=\vec{u} - \tfrac12\,\vec{v}</m>, drawn here in black.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-uv-solution">
      <caption>Construction of <m>\vec{w}=\vec{u} - \tfrac12\,\vec{v}</m> (black) using a tip-to-tail method.</caption>
      <image width="80%">
              <description>
        Same grid with u (blue) and v (red) from the origin, plus the constructed vector w = u minus one-half v in purple from the origin to the appropriate tip.
      </description>
        <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]

  % --- Large grid and axes ---
  \draw[gray!50] (-1.5,-2.5) grid (8.5,6.5);
  \draw[->] (-1.5,0) -- (8.8,0) node[right] {$x$};
  \draw[->] (0,-2.5) -- (0,6.8) node[above] {$y$};

  % --- Given vectors ---
  \draw[->, very thick, blue] (0,0) -- (5,2)
    node[midway, below right] {$\vec{u}$};
  \draw[->, very thick, red] (0,0) -- (2,6)
    node[midway, left] {$\vec{v}$};

  % --- Helper:  (1/2) v, shown faint (not required but helps visualize)
  \draw[->, thick, red!40!black!40] (0,0) -- (1,3)
    node[pos=0.65, right, text=red!40!black!60] {$\tfrac12\,\vec{v}$};

  % --- Place - (1/2) v at tip of u (dashed helper from tip of u)
  \draw[->, very thick, red!50!black, dashed] (5,2) -- (4,-1)
    node[midway, right, text=red!60!black] {$-\tfrac12\,\vec{v}$};

  % --- Resultant w = u - (1/2) v in purple from origin to the tip of the dashed helper
  \draw[->, ultra thick, black] (0,0) -- (4,-1)
    node[below right, text=black] {$\vec{w}$};

  % Tick marks
  \foreach \x in {-1,0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8}
    \draw[gray!80] (\x,0.1)--(\x,-0.1);
  \foreach \y in {-2,-1,0,1,2,3,4,5,6}
    \draw[gray!80] (0.1,\y)--(-0.1,\y);

\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="vector-magnitude-3d">
  <!-- <title>Magnitude of a Three-Dimensional Vector</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Compute the magnitude of the vector     <m>
      \vec{w} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -4 \\ 12 \end{bmatrix}.
    </m>
    </p>

  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Recall that the magnitude of a vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> is
    </p>

    <me>
      \|\vec{w}\| = \sqrt{w_1^2 + w_2^2 + w_3^2}.
    </me>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      <m>\|\vec{w}\| = 13.</m>
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Using the formula
    </p>
    <me>
      \|\vec{w}\| = \sqrt{3^2 + (-4)^2 + 12^2},
    </me>

    <p>
      compute:
    </p>

    <me>
      3^2 = 9,\qquad (-4)^2 = 16,\qquad 12^2 = 144.
    </me>

    <p>
      Sum the squares:
    </p>

    <me>
      9 + 16 + 144 = 169.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore,
    </p>

    <me>
      \|\vec{w}\| = \sqrt{169} = 13.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matrix-algebra-basics-with-inverse">
  <!-- <title>Basic Matrix Algebra and Computing an Inverse</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Let
    </p>

    <me>
      A =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      2 \amp -1 \\
      3 \amp 4
      \end{bmatrix},
      \qquad
      B =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 5 \\
      -2 \amp 0
      \end{bmatrix},
      \qquad
      \vec{v} =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      3 \\
      -1
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Compute each of the following:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li><m>A + B</m></li>
      <li><m>2A - B</m></li>
      <li><m>A\vec{v}</m></li>
      <li>Compute the inverse <m>A^{-1}</m>.</li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      For matrix addition, subtraction, or scalar multiplication, work entry‑wise.  
      For <m>A\vec{v}</m>, use
    </p>

    <me>
      A\vec{v}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      a_{11}v_1 + a_{12}v_2 \\
      a_{21}v_1 + a_{22}v_2
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      For the inverse of a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{bmatrix}
      a \amp b \\
      c \amp d
      \end{bmatrix},
    </me>

    <p>
      use the formula
    </p>

    <me>
      \dfrac{1}{ad - bc}
      \begin{bmatrix}
      d \amp -b \\
      -c \amp a
      \end{bmatrix},
      \qquad
      \text{provided } ad - bc \neq 0.
    </me>

  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      <m>A + B =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      3 \amp 4 \\
      1 \amp 4
      \end{bmatrix}</m>,
      <m>2A - B =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      3 \amp -7 \\
      8 \amp 8
      \end{bmatrix}</m>,
      <m>A\vec{v} =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      7 \\
      5
      \end{bmatrix}</m>,
      and
      </p>

      <me>
      A^{-1} =
      \frac{1}{11}
      \begin{bmatrix}
      4 \amp 1 \\
      -3 \amp 2
      \end{bmatrix}.
      </me>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      (a)  Add matrices entry‑wise:
    </p>

    <me>
      A + B
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      2+1 \amp -1+5 \\
      3+(-2) \amp 4+0
      \end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      3 \amp 4 \\
      1 \amp 4
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      (b)  Compute <m>2A</m> then subtract <m>B</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      2A =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      4 \amp -2 \\
      6 \amp 8
      \end{bmatrix},
    </me>

    <me>
      2A - B
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      4-1 \amp -2-5 \\
      6-(-2) \amp 8-0
      \end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      3 \amp -7 \\
      8 \amp 8
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      (c)  Multiply <m>A</m> by <m>\vec{v}</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      A\vec{v}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      2(3) + (-1)(-1) \\
      3(3) + 4(-1)
      \end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      6+1 \\
      9-4
      \end{bmatrix}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      7 \\
      5
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      (d)  Compute <m>A^{-1}</m>.  
      For
    </p>

    <me>
      A =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      2 \amp -1 \\
      3 \amp 4
      \end{bmatrix},
    </me>

    <p>
      the determinant is
    </p>

    <me>
      \det(A) = 2\cdot 4 - (-1)\cdot 3 = 8 + 3 = 11.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus,
    </p>

    <me>
      A^{-1}
      =
      \frac{1}{11}
      \begin{bmatrix}
      4 \amp 1 \\
      -3 \amp 2
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

  </solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="elimination-corrected">
  <!-- <title>Solving a System by Elimination</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the following linear system using elimination:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{aligned}
      2x + 3y \amp= 7, \\
      4x - y \amp= 1.
      \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>Show all elimination steps clearly.</p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Eliminate <m>x</m> by multiplying the first equation by <m>-2</m> and adding it to the second.  
      After that, solve for <m>y</m> and substitute back to find <m>x</m>.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      <m>x = \frac{5}{7}</m> and <m>y = \frac{13}{7}</m>.
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>The system is:</p>

    <me>
      \begin{aligned}
      2x + 3y \amp= 7, \\
      4x - y \amp= 1.
      \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>Multiply the second equation by <m>3</m> to eliminate <m>y</m>:</p>

    <me>
      12x - 3y = 3.
    </me>

    <p>Add this to the first equation:</p>

    <me>
      \begin{aligned}
      (12x - 3y) + (2x + 3y) \amp= 3 + 7, \\
      14x \amp= 10.
      \end{aligned}
    </me>

    <p>Thus,</p>

    <me>
      x = \frac{10}{14} = \frac{5}{7}.
    </me>

    <p>Substitute into <m>4x - y = 1</m>:</p>

    <me>
      4\left(\frac{5}{7}\right) - y = 1.
    </me>

    <p>Solve for <m>y</m>:</p>

    <me>
      \frac{20}{7} - y = 1, \\
      -y = 1 - \frac{20}{7}
           = -\frac{13}{7}, \\
      y = \frac{13}{7}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore, the solution is:
    </p>

    <me>
      x = \frac{5}{7}, \qquad y = \frac{13}{7}.
    </me>
  </solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="inverse-3x3-row-reduction">
  <!-- <title>Computing a \(3\times 3\) Inverse via Row Reduction</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Use elementary row operations on the augmented matrix <m>(A \mid I)</m> to compute <m>A^{-1}</m>, where
    </p>

    <me>
      A =
      \begin{bmatrix}
        2 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
        1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 1
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Show your row operations clearly and stop when you reach <m>(I \mid A^{-1})</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Form the augmented matrix <m>(A \mid I)</m> and use row operations to reduce the left block to the identity:
    </p>

    <me>
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
        2 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
        1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
      \end{array}
      \right].
    </me>

    <p>
      Aim for leading <m>1</m>s down the diagonal on the left, clearing above and below each pivot.
(Swapping rows early can simplify getting a pivot <m>1</m> in the first row.)
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      The inverse is
    </p>

    <me>
      A^{-1} =
      \begin{bmatrix}
        \tfrac{1}{3} \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \amp -\tfrac{1}{3} \\
        -\tfrac{1}{3} \amp \tfrac{2}{3} \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \\
        \tfrac{1}{3} \amp -\tfrac{2}{3} \amp \tfrac{2}{3}
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Start with the augmented matrix:
    </p>

    <me>
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
        2 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
        1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
      \end{array}
      \right].
    </me>

    <p>
      Swap <m>R_{1} \leftrightarrow R_{2}</m> to get a pivot <m>1</m> in the upper left:
    </p>

    <me>
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
        1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
        2 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
      \end{array}
      \right].
    </me>

    <p>
      Eliminate below the pivot in column <m>1</m>: <m>R_{2} \leftarrow R_{2} - 2R_{1}</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
        1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1
      \end{array}
      \right].
    </me>

    <p>
      Make a pivot <m>1</m> in row <m>2</m> column <m>2</m> by swapping <m>R_{2} \leftrightarrow R_{3}</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
        1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
        0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0
      \end{array}
      \right].
    </me>

    <p>
      Clear column <m>2</m> above and below the pivot: <m>R_{1} \leftarrow R_{1} - R_{2}</m>, <m>R_{3} \leftarrow R_{3} + 2R_{2}</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
        1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 2
      \end{array}
      \right].
    </me>

    <p>
      Make the pivot in row <m>3</m> column <m>3</m> a <m>1</m>: <m>R_{3} \leftarrow \tfrac{1}{3}R_{3}</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
        1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \amp -\tfrac{2}{3} \amp \tfrac{2}{3}
      \end{array}
      \right].
    </me>

    <p>
      Clear column <m>3</m> above the pivot: <m>R_{1} \leftarrow R_{1} + R_{3}</m>, <m>R_{2} \leftarrow R_{2} - R_{3}</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \left[
      \begin{array}{ccc|ccc}
        1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \amp -\tfrac{1}{3} \\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -\tfrac{1}{3} \amp \tfrac{2}{3} \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \amp -\tfrac{2}{3} \amp \tfrac{2}{3}
      \end{array}
      \right]
      \;=\;
      \left( I \;\middle|\;
      \begin{array}{ccc}
        \tfrac{1}{3} \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \amp -\tfrac{1}{3} \\
        -\tfrac{1}{3} \amp \tfrac{2}{3} \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \\
        \tfrac{1}{3} \amp -\tfrac{2}{3} \amp \tfrac{2}{3}
      \end{array}
      \right).
    </me>

    <p>
      Hence,
    </p>

    <me>
      A^{-1} =
      \begin{bmatrix}
        \tfrac{1}{3} \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \amp -\tfrac{1}{3} \\
        -\tfrac{1}{3} \amp \tfrac{2}{3} \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \\
        \tfrac{1}{3} \amp -\tfrac{2}{3} \amp \tfrac{2}{3}
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="column-space-independent-set">
  <!-- <title>Finding Independent Columns that Span the Column Space</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the matrix
    </p>

    <me>
      A =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      2 \amp 4 \amp 6 \\
      1 \amp 3 \amp 5 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 2
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Use elimination to find a <em>linearly independent</em> set of columns of <m>A</m> 
      that still spans the column space.  
      (Your answer should list which columns form such a set.)
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Perform row‑reduction on <m>A</m> and identify the <em>pivot columns</em>.  
      These columns form a linearly independent set that spans the column space.
    </p>

    <p>
      You may row‑reduce the entire matrix at once, or you may augment with 
      column labels and track which columns contain pivots.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      Columns <m>1</m> and <m>2</m> form a linearly independent set that spans 
      the column space of <m>A</m>.
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Start with <m>A</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{bmatrix}
      2 \amp 4 \amp 6 \\
      1 \amp 3 \amp 5 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 2
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      First, swap <m>R_1</m> and <m>R_2</m> so that the top-left pivot is <m>1</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 3 \amp 5 \\
      2 \amp 4 \amp 6 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 2
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Eliminate below the pivot in column 1: <m>R_2 \leftarrow R_2 - 2R_1</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 3 \amp 5 \\
      0 \amp -2 \amp -4 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 2
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Make a pivot in column 2 by swapping <m>R_2</m> and <m>R_3</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 3 \amp 5 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\
      0 \amp -2 \amp -4
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Now eliminate below: <m>R_3 \leftarrow R_3 + 2R_2</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 3 \amp 5 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      The row‑reduced form shows pivots in columns 1 and 2.  
      Column 3 has no pivot, so it is a linear combination of the first two.
    </p>

    <p>
      Therefore, the first two columns of <m>A</m> form a linearly independent
      set that spans the column space.
    </p>

    <me>
      \{\text{column }1,\; \text{column }2\}.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="kernel-dimension-exam">
  <!-- <title>Finding the Kernel and Its Dimension</title> -->

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the matrix
    </p>

    <me>
      A =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
      2 \amp 4 \amp -2 \\
      3 \amp 6 \amp -3
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      <ol>
        <li>Use row reduction to find a basis for the kernel of <m>A</m>.</li>
        <li>Determine the dimension of the kernel.</li>
        <li>Is the kernel a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>?  Briefly justify your answer.</li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <hint>
    <p>
      Row‑reduce <m>A</m>.  
      You should find that the rows are multiples of one another.  
      After reducing, express the solution to <m>A\vec{x} = \vec{0}</m> in parametric vector form.
    </p>

    <p>
      Remember: the kernel of a matrix is always a subspace of the domain.  
      Once you have the parametric form, count the number of free variables to determine the dimension.
    </p>
  </hint>

  <answer>
    <p>
      A basis for the kernel is
    </p>

    <me>
      \left\{
      \begin{bmatrix}
      -2 \\
      1 \\
      0
      \end{bmatrix},
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \\
      0 \\
      1
      \end{bmatrix}
      \right\}.
    </me>

    <p>
      The kernel has dimension <m>2</m>.  
      Yes, it is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
    </p>
  </answer>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Begin with
    </p>

    <me>
      A =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
      2 \amp 4 \amp -2 \\
      3 \amp 6 \amp -3
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Notice that <m>R_2 = 2R_1</m> and <m>R_3 = 3R_1</m>.  
      Perform row reduction:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
      2 \amp 4 \amp -2 \\
      3 \amp 6 \amp -3
      \end{bmatrix}
      \xrightarrow{R_2 - 2R_1,\; R_3 - 3R_1}
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve <m>A\vec{x}=0</m> from the single non‑zero equation:
    </p>

    <me>
      x_1 + 2x_2 - x_3 = 0
      \quad\Rightarrow\quad
      x_1 = -2x_2 + x_3.
    </me>

    <p>
      Let <m>x_2 = s</m> and <m>x_3 = t</m> (free variables).  
      Then
    </p>

    <me>
      \vec{x}
      =
      \begin{bmatrix}
      -2s + t \\
      s \\
      t
      \end{bmatrix}
      =
      s
      \begin{bmatrix}
      -2 \\
      1 \\
      0
      \end{bmatrix}
      +
      t
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \\
      0 \\
      1
      \end{bmatrix}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore a basis for the kernel is
    </p>

    <me>
      \left\{
      \begin{bmatrix}
      -2 \\
      1 \\
      0
      \end{bmatrix},
      \begin{bmatrix}
      1 \\
      0 \\
      1
      \end{bmatrix}
      \right\}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Since there are two free variables, the dimension of the kernel is <m>2</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The kernel of any linear transformation (and therefore any matrix) is always a subspace of its domain, 
      so here it is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>

</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>
</handout>